# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: kestra-orchestration
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:kestra-orchestration/data-pipeline] In computing, a **pipeline**, also known as a **data pipeline**, is a set of data processing elements connected in series, where the output of one element is the input of the next one.
[src:kestra-orchestration/data-pipeline] The elements of a pipeline are often executed in parallel or in time-sliced fashion.
[src:kestra-orchestration/data-pipeline] Some amount of buffer storage is often inserted between elements.
[src:kestra-orchestration/data-pipeline] Pipelining is a commonly used concept in everyday life.
[src:kestra-orchestration/data-pipeline] For example, in the assembly line of a car factory, each specific task—such as installing the engine, installing the hood, and installing the wheels—is often done by a separate work station.
[src:kestra-orchestration/data-pipeline] The stations carry out their tasks in parallel, each on a different car.
[src:kestra-orchestration/data-pipeline] Once a car has had one task performed, it moves to the next station.
[src:kestra-orchestration/data-pipeline] Variations in the time needed to complete the tasks can be accommodated by "buffering" (holding one or more cars in a space between the stations) and/or by "stalling" (temporarily halting the upstream stations), until the next station becomes available.
[src:kestra-orchestration/data-pipeline] Suppose that assembling one car requires three tasks that take 20, 10, and 15 minutes, respectively.
[src:kestra-orchestration/data-pipeline] Then, if all three tasks were performed by a single station, the factory would output one car every 45 minutes.
[src:kestra-orchestration/data-pipeline] By using a pipeline of three stations, the factory would output the first car in 45 minutes, and then a new one every 20 minutes.
[src:kestra-orchestration/data-pipeline] As this example shows, pipelining does not decrease the latency, that is, the total time for one item to go through the whole system.
[src:kestra-orchestration/data-pipeline] It does however increase the system's throughput, that is, the rate at which new items are processed after the first one.
[src:kestra-orchestration/data-pipeline] In computing, a pipeline or data pipeline is a set of data processing elements connected in series, where the output of one element is the input of the next one.
[src:kestra-orchestration/data-pipeline] If a pipeline consists of idempotent steps, these can be rerun without altering the outcome beyond the initial run.
[src:kestra-orchestration/data-pipeline] This is advantageous in terms of reliability and maintenance.
[src:kestra-orchestration/data-pipeline] Since the throughput of a pipeline cannot be better than that of its slowest element, the designer should try to divide the work and resources among the stages so that they all take the same time to complete their tasks.
[src:kestra-orchestration/data-pipeline] In the car assembly example above, if the three tasks took 15 minutes each, instead of 20, 10, and 15 minutes, the latency would still be 45 minutes, but a new car would then be finished every 15 minutes, instead of 20.
[src:kestra-orchestration/data-pipeline] Under ideal circumstances, if all processing elements are synchronized and take the same amount of time to process, then each item can be received by each element just as it is released by the previous one, in a single clock cycle.
[src:kestra-orchestration/data-pipeline] That way, the items will flow through the pipeline at a constant speed, like waves in a water channel.
[src:kestra-orchestration/data-pipeline] In such "wave pipelines", no synchronization or buffering is needed between the stages, besides the storage needed for the data items.
[src:kestra-orchestration/data-pipeline] More generally, buffering between the pipeline stages is necessary when the processing times are irregular, or when items may be created or destroyed along the pipeline.
[src:kestra-orchestration/data-pipeline] For example, in a graphics pipeline that processes triangles to be rendered on the screen, an element that checks the visibility of each triangle may discard the triangle if it is invisible, or may output two or more triangular pieces of the element if they are partly hidden.
[src:kestra-orchestration/data-pipeline] Buffering is also needed to accommodate irregularities in the rates at which the application feeds items to the first stage and consumes the output of the last one.
[src:kestra-orchestration/data-pipeline] The buffer between two stages may be simply a hardware register with suitable synchronization and signalling logic between the two stages.
[src:kestra-orchestration/data-pipeline] When a stage A stores a data item in the register, it sends a "data available" signal to the next stage B.
[src:kestra-orchestration/data-pipeline] Once B has used that data, it responds with a "data received" signal to A.
[src:kestra-orchestration/data-pipeline] Stage A halts, waiting for this signal, before storing the next data item into the register.
[src:kestra-orchestration/data-pipeline] Stage B halts, waiting for the "data available" signal, if it is ready to process the next item but stage A has not provided it yet.
[src:kestra-orchestration/data-pipeline] If the processing times of an element are variable, the whole pipeline may often have to stop, waiting for that element and all the previous ones to consume the items in their input buffers.
[src:kestra-orchestration/data-pipeline] The frequency of such pipeline stalls can be reduced by providing space for more than one item in the input buffer of that stage.
[src:kestra-orchestration/data-pipeline] Such a multiple-item buffer is usually implemented as a first-in, first-out queue.
[src:kestra-orchestration/data-pipeline] The upstream stage may still have to be halted when the queue gets full, but the frequency of those events will decrease as more buffer slots are provided.
[src:kestra-orchestration/data-pipeline] Queueing theory can tell the number of buffer slots needed, depending on the variability of the processing times and on the desired performance.
[src:kestra-orchestration/data-pipeline] If some stage takes (or may take) much longer than the others, and cannot be sped up, the designer can provide two or more processing elements to carry out that task in parallel, with a single input buffer and a single output buffer.
[src:kestra-orchestration/data-pipeline] As each element finishes processing its current data item, it delivers it to the common output buffer, and takes the next data item from the common input buffer.
[src:kestra-orchestration/data-pipeline] This concept of "non-linear" or "dynamic" pipeline is exemplified by shops or banks that have two or more cashiers serving clients from a single waiting queue.
[src:kestra-orchestration/data-pipeline] In some applications, the processing of an item Y by a stage A may depend on the results or effect of processing a previous item X by some later stage B of the pipeline.
[src:kestra-orchestration/data-pipeline] In that case, stage A cannot correctly process item Y until item X has cleared stage B.
[src:kestra-orchestration/data-pipeline] This situation occurs very often in instruction pipelines.
[src:kestra-orchestration/data-pipeline] For example, suppose that Y is an arithmetic instruction that reads the contents of a register that was supposed to have been modified by an earlier instruction X.
[src:kestra-orchestration/data-pipeline] Let A be the stage that fetches the instruction operands, and B be the stage that writes the result to the specified register.
[src:kestra-orchestration/data-pipeline] If stage A tries to process instruction Y before instruction X reaches stage B, the register may still contain the old value, and the effect of Y would be incorrect.
[src:kestra-orchestration/data-pipeline] In order to handle such conflicts correctly, the pipeline must be provided with extra circuitry or logic that detects them and takes the appropriate action.
[src:kestra-orchestration/data-pipeline] Rather than halt while waiting for X to be finished, stage A may guess whether the branch will be taken or not, and fetch the next instruction Y based on that guess.
[src:kestra-orchestration/data-pipeline] If the guess later turns out to be incorrect (hopefully rarely), the system would have to backtrack and resume with the correct choice.
[src:kestra-orchestration/data-pipeline] To be effectively implemented, data pipelines need a CPU scheduling strategy to dispatch work to the available CPU cores, and the usage of data structures on which the pipeline stages will operate on.
[src:kestra-orchestration/data-pipeline] For example, UNIX derivatives may pipeline commands connecting various processes' standard IO, using the pipes implemented by the operating system.
[src:kestra-orchestration/data-pipeline] Some operating systems may provide UNIX-like syntax to string several program runs in a pipeline, but implement the latter as simple serial execution, rather than true pipelining—namely, by waiting for each program to finish before starting the next one.
[src:kestra-orchestration/data-pipeline] Lower level approaches may rely on the threads provided by the operating system to schedule work on the stages: both thread pool-based implementations or on a one-thread-per-stage are viable, and exist.
[src:kestra-orchestration/data-pipeline] Other strategies relying on cooperative multitasking exist, that do not need multiple threads of execution and hence additional CPU cores, such as using a round-robin scheduler with a coroutine-based framework.
[src:kestra-orchestration/data-pipeline] In this context, each stage may be instantiated with its own coroutine, yielding control back to the scheduler after finishing its round task.
[src:kestra-orchestration/data-pipeline] This approach may need careful control over the process' stages to avoid them abuse their time slice.
[src:kestra-orchestration/data-pipeline] A pipelined system typically requires more resources (circuit elements, processing units, computer memory, etc.) than one that executes one batch at a time, because its stages cannot share those resources, and because buffering and additional synchronization logic may be needed between the elements.
[src:kestra-orchestration/data-pipeline] Moreover, the transfer of items between separate processing elements may increase the latency, especially for long pipelines.
[src:kestra-orchestration/data-pipeline] The additional complexity cost of pipelining may be considerable if there are dependencies between the processing of different items, especially if a guess-and-backtrack strategy is used to handle them.
[src:kestra-orchestration/data-pipeline] Indeed, the cost of implementing that strategy for complex instruction sets has motivated some radical proposals to simplify computer architecture, such as RISC and VLIW.
[src:kestra-orchestration/data-pipeline] Compilers also have been burdened with the task of rearranging the machine instructions so as to improve the performance of instruction pipelines.
[src:kestra-orchestration/data-pipeline] In recent years the demands on applications and their underlying hardware have been significant.
[src:kestra-orchestration/data-pipeline] For example, building pipelines with single node applications that trawl through the data row by row is no longer feasible with the volume and variety of big data.
[src:kestra-orchestration/data-pipeline] However, with the advent of data analytics engines such as Hadoop, or more recently Apache Spark, it's been possible to distribute large datasets across multiple processing nodes, allowing applications to reach heights of efficiency several hundred times greater than was thought possible before.
[src:kestra-orchestration/data-pipeline] The effect of this today is that even a mid-level PC using distributed processing in this fashion can handle the building and running of big data pipelines.
[src:kestra-orchestration/develop-readme-md] Kestra is an open-source, event-driven orchestration platform for data, AI, and infrastructure workflows.
[src:kestra-orchestration/develop-readme-md] It unifies **scheduled** and **event-driven** automation behind a declarative, language-agnostic interface.
[src:kestra-orchestration/develop-readme-md] By bringing **Infrastructure as Code** best practices to your data, process, and microservice pipelines, you can build reliable workflows directly from the UI in just a few lines of YAML.
[src:kestra-orchestration/develop-readme-md] 🧑‍💻 The YAML definition gets automatically adjusted any time you make changes to a workflow from the UI or via an API call.
[src:kestra-orchestration/develop-readme-md] Therefore, the orchestration logic is **always managed declaratively in code**, even if you modify your workflows in other ways (UI, CI/CD, Terraform, API calls).
[src:kestra-orchestration/develop-readme-md] Deploy Kestra on Google Cloud Infrastructure Manager using our Terraform module.
[src:kestra-orchestration/develop-readme-md] Check our Installation Guide for other deployment options (Docker Compose, Podman, Kubernetes, AWS, GCP, Azure, and more).
[src:kestra-orchestration/develop-readme-md] Access the Kestra UI at http://localhost:8080 and start building your first flow!
[src:kestra-orchestration/develop-readme-md] Run the flow and see the output in the UI!
[src:kestra-orchestration/develop-readme-md] Kestra's functionality is extended through a rich ecosystem of plugins that empower you to run tasks anywhere and code in any language, including Python, Node.js, R, Go, Shell, and more.
[src:kestra-orchestration/develop-readme-md] Kestra's plugin ecosystem is continually expanding, allowing you to tailor the platform to your specific needs.
[src:kestra-orchestration/develop-readme-md] Whether you're orchestrating complex data pipelines, automating scripts across multiple environments, or integrating with cloud services, there's likely a plugin to assist.
[src:kestra-orchestration/develop-readme-md] And if not, you can always build your own plugins to extend Kestra's capabilities.
[src:kestra-orchestration/develop-readme-md] 🧑‍💻 **Note:** This is just a glimpse of what Kestra plugins can do.
[src:kestra-orchestration/develop-readme-md] Explore the full list on our Plugins Page.
[src:kestra-orchestration/develop-readme-md] Create custom plugins to extend Kestra's capabilities.
[src:kestra-orchestration/develop-readme-md] Check out our Plugin Developer Guide to get started.
